<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-166-936  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 166 936.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  March 16 1989 n1155 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Rules and relations: the separation of rules from programs anddata promises greater flexibility in database management.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Butler, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The whole of computing is based on two good ideas: that computerinstructions can be held in memory, and that data can be separatedfrom programs.andP;  A third idea is emerging, however: that rules canbe separated from programs and data.andP;  Common examples of rulesinclude price discounting rules in sales order processing, or thecomplex rules in underwriting systems.andP;  The trigger, which isusually an SQL procedure, is one mechanism for implementing rulesas separate entities from programs and data.andP;  Another is the useof constraints, which restrict the values in a data base based onother values in the data base.andP;  An extension of both of thesemechanisms is stored procedures, which are held in a compiledformat within the data base, and offer trigger and constraint-likefunctionality as a sub-set of their capabilities.andP;  Expert systemscan also be used to separate rules from programs and data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsData Base DesignRelational DBMSData StructuresNew TechniqueCoding.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>